    <td class="style2">
      <p class="style7">Why is it special?</p>
      <p>
        RSPB Loch of Kinnordy is a wetland oasis. It is special for many
        reasons, not only does it have many designations (SSSI, SPA and RAMSAR)
        for its habitat, breeding birds and wintering wildfowl, but it as an
        important area for visitors. Birdwatchers, photographers and walkers
        alike enjoy the hides and trails.
      </p>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table>
<table width="1024" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
  <tr>
    <td>
      <p class="style2">
        <span class="style7"
          >Why don&rsquo;t I see grebes or gulls here anymore?</span
        >
      </p>
      <p class="style2">
        Black-necked grebe numbers declined from 1994, until in 1999 only one
        pair attempted to breed, and the last attempt by any was 2001.
        Black-necked grebe have now virtually disappeared from Scotland.<br />
        The gull colony also declined, and only a small number return each
        spring. Between 2000-2006 these birds would desert the nests before
        chicks hatched. The reason for this is still uncertain, but
        possibilities include:<br />
        &bull; changes in the vegetation from low lying bogbean islands to
        taller plants and eventually trees, restricting visibility of birds
        sitting on nests and providing cover for predators<br />
        &bull; natural movement of birds, both species are known to change
        breeding sites suddenly<br />
        &bull; increase in predation of nests noticeable particularly as the
        colony became smaller and fewer birds were present for protection.
      </p>
      <p class="style2">
        From 2007 &ndash; 2011 the Black-headed Gull colony had shown signs of
        recovery with birds staying through to hatching but with high levels of
        predation being a continued issue, the colony has been in decline since
        2011. Black headed gulls are a social bird, they nest in large colonies
        which give them safety in numbers - they can quickly alert one another
        to a threat of predators. The adult birds will alarm call and dive bomb
        the predator with the aim of keeping the chicks safe. A reduced number
        of adults mean this alarm system isn&rsquo;t as effective, so predation
        poses a much bigger threat.&nbsp; For this reason, in 2016, the RSPB
        took action by creating a raft for black headed birds to nest on. This
        raft floats between the natural bogbean islands. It has a gravel bed
        inside for gulls to nest on and Perspex sides keeping mammalian
        predators out. It is hoped that by giving the gulls a safe place to nest
        it will allow the population to increase and so allow that natural alarm
        call system to work effectively in the future.
      </p>
