      <p class="style7">Marsh Vegetation Management:</p>
      <p>
        Removing the willow from the west end uncovered marsh vegetation which
        is ecologically valuable, but will become rank and eventually develop
        back to willow carr if left unmanaged. Initial small trials with a
        strimmer demonstrated the value of cutting this vegetation in the
        summer, leaving shorter vegetation for the following spring, which is
        good for breeding waders. A less labour intensive method, and better as
        there are no cuttings left, is to graze the area, so in 2003 a local
        grazier introduced a few Highland cattle to the reserve and these now
        permanently graze around the edge of the marsh. In 2010 fencing and
        sowing of species rich grassland seed mix was completed on a small field
        to the north of the reserve and this is managed through grazing provided
        by the Highland cattle. Livestock has grazed at Kinnordy ever since and
        as well as cattle over the years there have been Konic ponies and
        Hebridean sheep.
      </p>
